[1]
Date: 30 Mar 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hong Kong - Department of Health 30 Mar 2003 [edited]
<http://www.info.gov.hk/dh/new/index.htm>

[A] Update on atypical pneumonia 30 Mar 2003
The following is jointly issued by the Department of Health and the
Hospital Authority:
An additional 60 patients with symptoms of atypical pneumonia were admitted
to public hospitals as of 1 PM 30 Mar 2003. They include 6 healthcare
workers and 36 patients from Amoy Gardens. The remaining 18 were new
patients and contacts of patients with atypical pneumonia.
17 patients, including 12 healthcare workers and medical students of Prince
of Wales Hospital, were discharged from hospital today. A total of 60
patients to date have recovered from atypical pneumonia and been discharged.
Currently, 52 patients are receiving treatment in the intensive care unit.
A 74-year-old female patient with a history of other diseases died in
United Christian Hospital this morning. This brings to 13 the total number
of patients died with atypical pneumonia in public hospitals.
The cumulative figure for patients admitted to public hospitals with
atypical pneumonia is 530, starting from 12 Mar 2003.
The breakdown of figures is as follows: (The numbers in bracket are those
with pneumonia symptoms)
Health care workers of Hospitals/Clinics and medical students 162 (162)
36 of the patients were discharged
Patients, family members & visitors 368 (368)
24 of the patients were discharged
Total admission 530 (530)
60 were discharged
[B] Flight passengers urged to contact DH 30 Mar 2003
The Department of Health (DH) on 30 Mar 2003 called on passengers who had
travelled from Beijing to Hong Kong on flight KA 901(Dragonair) on 26 Mar
2003 to call DH's hotline 2961 8968 for health advice on atypical pneumonia
and surveillance. The hotline will be manned from noon to 5 PM 30 Mar 2003
and from 9 AM to 5 PM on weekdays.
The plea was made as DH's investigation found that a Hong Kong man who had
taken the flight developed symptoms of severe acute respiratory syndrome
during his stay in Beijing. He was later confirmed to have contracted the
disease. DH has informed the Airport Authority and the airline. Advice was
also given to the airline concerned to disinfect the airplanes. DH is
tracing the crew members and passengers who had taken these 2 flights, for
surveillance purposes.
--
