[3]
Date: 30 Mar 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Health Canada [edited]
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/english/protection/warnings/2003/2003_11update15.htm>

As of 30 Mar 2003, Health Canada has received reports of approximately 98
probable or suspect cases of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in
Ontario, British Columbia, Alberta and New Brunswick. There have been 4
deaths in Canada. All Canadian cases have occurred in persons who have
traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS cases in the household or in a
health-care setting. The information contained in this update is based on
the best available information Health Canada has at this time.
Health Canada is changing the way it is reporting probable and suspect
cases of SARS to ensure consistency in reporting across the country.
"Probable" cases of SARS are similar to suspect cases, but often they have
a more severe illness, with progressive shortness of breath and difficulty
breathing, and in some cases, chest x-rays show signs of atypical pneumonia.
A "suspect" case of SARS is a person who fits into one of the following 2
categories: a person who develops fever and one or more respiratory
symptoms, including cough, shortness of breath or difficulty breathing,
within 10 days of returning from travel to areas in Asia where SARS cases
are being reported, or a person who develops fever and one or more
respiratory symptoms, including cough, shortness of breath or difficulty
breathing, within 10 days of having had close contact with a "probable"
case of SARS (i.e., within one metre).
The details of the cases to date are as follows:
Ontario is reporting approximately 81 probable and suspect cases. All cases
have occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS
cases in the household or in a health-care setting.
British Columbia is reporting 2 probable and 8 suspect cases.
New Brunswick is reporting one suspect case.
Saskatchewan is reporting one suspect case.
Alberta is reporting 5 suspect cases.
Manitoba is no longer reporting any suspect or probable cases.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Today's reports reflect an increase in 60 cases in Hong Kong, and 2
additional cases in Singapore. The number of cases reported in Canada has
increased from 37 to 98, but the latter figure is a combination of
suspected and probable cases, whereas the 37 referred to only probable
cases. Information on a global worldwide update was not available as of
the time of preparation of this update.
With the exception of the ongoing outbreak in Hong Kong (and possibly in
mainland China), the outbreak of SARS in other areas seems to be following
a pattern consistent with a requirement of close contact with an actively
ill case of SARS for transmission to occur. One can't help but muse on the
definition of close contact in different environments, and in those areas
with high population density, what might be a casual, non-close contact in
other areas is close enough to allow for transmission in an area with
higher population density. This moderator is reminded of studies conducted
on the baseline incidence of poliomyelitis in India back in the early
80s. It was generally accepted that polio was more of an "urban disease"
with higher incidences observed in urban areas. Results of studies on the
baseline incidence of polio in a highly populated state revealed that the
rural incidence was on a par with the urban incidence. Our interpretation
of this observation was that the standard western definition of urban vs.
rural was based on population density, where rural areas had a markedly
lower population density than urban areas. In the highly populated
districts of India, rural areas had population densities similar to many
western urban areas. Hence, rather than being an urban disease, polio was
more of a high population density disease. Again, food for thought here...
- Mod.MPP]
